
What is APR?
APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure of the annual cost of borrowing money, expressed as a percentage. This includes not only the interest you pay on your loan but also any fees associated with getting that loan. APR helps consumers compare different loan offers more accurately because it gives them a clearer picture of the true cost of borrowing over a year.

For example, if you're considering two credit card options, one with an annual percentage rate (APR) of 18% and another with an APR of 25%, the second card would actually be more expensive to borrow from despite having a lower stated interest rate. This is because it includes additional fees that make up for the difference in APRs.

When comparing loans or credit cards, always look at the APR to get a complete understanding of the loan's cost. It's crucial information when making financial decisions.
